x4freetext: Preliminary report
Ion source: Incident protons were generated as
secondary beam. TOF method with a pair of Pilot U
scintillators was adopted for the separation of the
protons from the pions.
- Target is natural.
- Chemical-form of target is element. Chemical purity
- Physical-form of target is solid.
- Target-thickness: Target was a rectangular
parallelepiped 15x15x20cm**3
Time difference between prompt gamma emission
(assumed to be emitted when neutron were
scattered by target) and neutron detection are
used to deduce outgoing neutron above 2.5 MeV
Below 2.5 MeV unfolding analysis was used
because scattered neutron has some delay in the
flight time due to multiple scattering in thick
target).

x4codes.hlp: High Energy Accelerator Res. Org. (KEK), Tsukuba, Japan

x4freetext: pi2 beam line of the 12 GeV Proton
Synchrotron
Neutron spectra by the unfolding analysis are
adopted for the neutron below 2.5 MeV.
- Detector resolution: Outgoing neutron energy
dependence of neutron detection efficiency is shown
in Table 2.
- Efficiency: Outgoing neutron energy dependence of
neutron detection efficiency is shown in Fig.5.
NE213, used as neutron detectors. These were of
cylindrical shapes of 12.7 cm in diameter and
12.7 cm in thickness. The pulse height of the
neutron detectors was calibrated using
gamma-rays from 137Cs, 60Co and 241Am-Be. The
neutron detection efficiency was obtained from
calculation results of SCINFUL-R [S. Meigo,
Nucl. Instr. Meth. A401(1997)365] and CECIL
[R.A. Cecil et al., Nucl. Instr. Meth.
NE102A, used as veto counters to reject the
detection of the charged particles, placed at a
distance of 2 cm from the surface of the NE213
- Outgoing neutron energy dependences of uncertainties
due to detection efficiency, number of projectile,
and neutron flux are shown in Table 2.
- Outgoing neutron energy dependences of statistical
uncertainty is given in Table 2.
